However, the obtained CDs undergo self-quenching in solid state due to the aggregation of CDs, which seriously deteriorates their PL performance and greatly hinders the development of CDs-based LEDs [60]. Incorporation of CDs into PVA, PMMA, inorganic salts, silica and other solid-state matrices has been commonly used to avoid this undesirable effect [61]. Specifically, the aggregated CDs directly contact with each other in the solid state, resulting a shortened distance that is less than Föster distance between interparticles (Fig. 6
                        ). Therefore, the Föster resonance energy transfer (FRET) accompanying aggregation is the root cause of PL self-quenching. Upon doping CDs into composites, the interparticle spacing is extended because of effective dispersion of solid-state matrices [62], thereby minimizing the self-quenching effect of CD in the aggregation state. Due to its high transmission, good water solubility, and easy processing, PVA was selected as the matrix to disperse CDs in the present study. The abundant surface PVA chains was able to prevent the graphitizing cores from π-π interactions (Fig. 6). Thus, the CDs particles embedded in the PVA kept an appropriate distance from each other, which avoided the FRET phenomenon and the consequent fluorescence quenching of solid-state CDs [6]. Indeed, the CDs/PVA films displayed strong photoluminescence under 365 nm excitation light, as shown in Fig. 7
                        . The color of CDs/PVA films was also tunable (ranging from blue, green to orange-red) by changing the types of the added CDs (Fig. S5 in Supporting Information).
